Dialogue: 0,0:00:01.30,0:00:05.30,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,她如影随形\N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}It's so close.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:07.70,0:00:12.31,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,几千年以来人们因为她的存在而得到欣慰 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}For thousands of years, Man has found comfort in its presence.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:16.88,0:00:19.53,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,她是旅行家夜晚的灯塔 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}It's been a beacon for nocturnal travelers,
Dialogue: 0,0:00:19.68,0:00:21.82,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,是农夫的计时器 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}a timekeeper for farmers,
Dialogue: 0,0:00:22.83,0:00:26.12,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,水手在海上的航标 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}and a location finder for sailors at sea.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:27.44,0:00:30.51,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,某些文明甚至把她作为神灵 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}For some cultures it's even been a god.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:31.30,0:00:35.22,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,她是人类唯一造访过的宇宙天体 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}It's the only cosmic body ever visited by human beings.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:35.49,0:00:39.20,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,而且现在美国航天局计划在那建立永久基地 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}And today NASA is planning a permanent outpost there.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:40.11,0:00:42.07,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,她是如何被放到首位的？\N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}But how did it get there in the first place?
Dialogue: 0,0:00:42.37,0:00:44.27,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,月亮是如何到来的呢？\N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}How did the Moon come to be?
Dialogue: 0,0:00:44.58,0:00:47.50,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,答案充满了惊奇和吸引力 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}The answer is more astounding and spectacular
Dialogue: 0,0:00:47.62,0:00:50.91,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,超过了地球上大多数人的想象 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}than most residents of Earth have ever imagined.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:52.00,0:00:57.00,Default,,0000,0000,0001,,{\fn华文楷体\fs16\1c&H3CF1F3&\b0}--==本影片由 {\1c&HFF8000&\b1}CMCT 团队{\fn华文楷体\1c&H3CF1F3&\b0} 荣誉出品==--\N更多精彩影视 请访问 {\fnCronos Pro Subhead\1c&HFF00FF&\b1}http://www.hdcmct.com{\r}
Dialogue: 0,0:00:58.00,0:01:03.00,Default,,0000,0000,0008,,{\fn华文楷体\fs16\1c&H3CF1F3&\b0}历史频道·宇宙第一季第5集 月球\N影片压制:暮云春树  字幕来源：射手网 调校：TIAN@CMCT 招募Q号: 76846146{\r}
Dialogue: 0,0:01:05.84,0:01:11.54,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,根据最新统计 太阳系里有150多颗卫星 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}At last count, over 150 moons populate our solar system.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:23.25,0:01:25.60,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,海王星有13颗 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}Neptune claims 13 of them.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:31.01,0:01:32.76,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,土星有48颗 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}Saturn has 48.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:39.23,0:01:42.84,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,木星竟然有62颗 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}And Jupiter host an astounding 62.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:56.79,0:01:59.76,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,另一方面地球却只有一颗 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}Earth, on the other hand, has just one.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:02.73,0:02:04.45,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,然而她却是特别的一颗 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}But it's a special one.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:08.56,0:02:13.50,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,我们的卫星--露娜(月神) 罗马人取的名字 有着不一般的大小 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}Our moon, Luna, as the Romans named it, is remarkable in its size.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:17.56,0:02:20.48,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,她不是太阳系里最大的卫星 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}It is by no means the largest moon in the solar system.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:20.85,0:02:22.52,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,其它几个要比她大 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}Several others are bigger.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:22.73,0:02:26.47,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,土星的一颗卫星提坦(土卫六)就是个例子 体积是月亮的两倍 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}One of Saturn's moon's Titan for instance, is twice the size.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:28.67,0:02:32.29,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,不过月亮对于地球却是最大的 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}But our moon is the largest, in relation to its host planet.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:34.34,0:02:37.68,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,她有地球的四分之一大小 与地球相比实在是大 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}It's a quarter the size of the Earth, It's really big compared to the Earth.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:38.95,0:02:41.66,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,如果你用望远镜在远距离观望地球 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}If you look to a telescope, at the Earth from a distance
Dialogue: 0,0:02:41.72,0:02:43.82,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,你将看到地球和这个大东西 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}you'd see the Earth and this other big thing.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:43.85,0:02:46.51,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,如果你看木星或其它行星 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}If you look at Jupiter, or any other planet,
Dialogue: 0,0:02:46.98,0:02:50.08,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,只能看到巨大的行星和所有微小的卫星在它的旁边 所以…\Nyou got the big planet and all tiny moons right next to it. So…
Dialogue: 0,0:02:50.29,0:02:53.76,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,我们的月亮要大得多 她只是…\Nour moon is so much bigger, and it's the only one of the…
Dialogue: 0,0:02:54.06,0:02:57.47,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,现在的八颗行星之一 就是这个情况 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}of the now eight planets, that has that situation.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:59.11,0:03:02.19,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,两者的相对大小如此接近 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}The relative sizes of the two bodies are close enough,
Dialogue: 0,0:03:02.34,0:03:06.62,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,某些天文学家很早就提及"地-月系统"\N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}that some astronomers goes so far as to refer to the "Earth-moon system"
Dialogue: 0,0:03:06.65,0:03:08.13,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,就象个双行星 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}as a double planet.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:11.44,0:03:16.84,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,地球到月亮的平均距离为234000英里 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}The mean distance from the Earth to the Moon is 234,000 miles.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:17.13,0:03:19.30,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,为期3天的飞行距离 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}A three-day fly through space.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:20.49,0:03:24.26,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,月球的直径大约为地球的四分之一 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}Luna's diameter is roughly one quarter the size of Earth,
Dialogue: 0,0:03:24.72,0:03:27.32,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,2160英里 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}measuring 2,160 miles.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:28.46,0:03:33.68,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,月球上的一天相当于地球的27.3天 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}A single day on the Moon is the equivalent of 27.3 Earth days.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:34.16,0:03:37.48,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,这是因为月球的一面始终对着我们 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}This is because one side of the Moon permanently faces us.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:38.11,0:03:40.73,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,月球一面固定对着地球 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}Luna is face-locked with our planet.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:41.55,0:03:44.23,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,因此月球必须是足足围绕地球转一圈 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}So the Moon must fully orbit the Earth, in order to make
Dialogue: 0,0:03:44.38,0:03:46.73,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,才能围绕着自己的轴线自转一圈 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}one complete rotation on its axes.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:46.97,0:03:49.97,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,就象孩子们玩的"围着萝西转圈圈"的游戏 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}Sort of like children in a game of "Ring around the Rosie".
Dialogue: 0,0:03:50.40,0:03:54.20,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,孩子们的脸始终朝着里面 手拉着手转着圈子 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}They always face inward, as they hold hands and move in a circle.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:00.58,0:04:05.55,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,0 点火 升空 已经升空…\NZero, all engines running. Liftoff. We have a liftoff…
Dialogue: 0,0:04:05.68,0:04:09.15,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,然而月球对地球是如此的密切 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}Yet as closely related as the Moon is to our Earth,
Dialogue: 0,0:04:09.41,0:04:13.00,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,对月球不仅仅是短暂的旅行 十分清楚 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}it would only take a brief visit to Luna, to make it quite clear
Dialogue: 0,0:04:13.18,0:04:17.13,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,事实上她与地球非常地不同 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}that it is in fact a very different world from our planet.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:23.60,0:04:26.07,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,这是一个非常危险的地方 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}And an exceedingly dangerous place.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:32.02,0:04:36.59,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,我们站在这 安静极了 鹰已经登陆 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}We're standing now. Tranquility base here. The Eagle has landed.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:36.94,0:04:39.84,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,当然没有空气 你需要太空服 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}There's no air of course. You need your space suit.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:43.32,0:04:47.39,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,确实月球完全没有大气层 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}Indeed, the Moon has absolutely no atmosphere at all.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:48.63,0:04:51.16,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,所以声音无法传播 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}So there is nothing to carry sound waves.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:54.20,0:04:57.88,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,如果你和朋友站在月球上试图交流 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}If you were standing on the Moon with a friend, and trying to converse,
Dialogue: 0,0:04:58.00,0:05:01.53,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,他是无法听到你说什么的 除非用无线电 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}the person wouldn't be able to hear you. Except by radio.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:01.95,0:05:05.00,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,我在月球上漫步了一天 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}I was strolling on the Moon one day,
Dialogue: 0,0:05:06.16,0:05:08.50,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,在快乐 快乐的…\Nin the merry, merry month of…
Dialogue: 0,0:05:08.50,0:05:10.08,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,-十二月 -不 是五月 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}- December. - No, May!
Dialogue: 0,0:05:12.63,0:05:16.61,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,没有大气层也意味着没有空气分子\N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}No atmosphere also means that there are no air molecules
Dialogue: 0,0:05:16.70,0:05:18.66,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,弥散太阳来的光线 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}to scatter light from the Sun.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:20.98,0:05:23.27,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,所以天空始终是黑暗的 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}So the sky is always black.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:30.64,0:05:33.81,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,地形对前景边亮少许有点帮助 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}And the landscape does little to help brighten the scene.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:35.43,0:05:39.20,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,单色调的 你知道吗没有很多颜色 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}Kind of monochromatic, you know, not much color there,
Dialogue: 0,0:05:39.28,0:05:41.60,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,岩石几乎是灰褐色的 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}The rocks are mostly gray-brown colors.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:41.82,0:05:46.53,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,她在一个方向上可能有点暖色调的 可能是向着太阳的缘故 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}It's maybe a little warmer tone in one direction, maybe towards the Sun, and
Dialogue: 0,0:05:46.87,0:05:50.46,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,而在其它方向去看 就是冷色调的 灰色调的 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}cooler tones, grayer tones, looking in other directions,
Dialogue: 0,0:05:51.16,0:05:52.90,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,不是五颜六色的 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}but not so colorful.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:55.03,0:05:59.49,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,极端的温度也是大煞游览的风景 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}Extreme temperatures will also add to the unpleasantness of a visit.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:01.32,0:06:04.30,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,冷热之间温度摆动是严酷的 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}The swings between hot and cold are brutal.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:04.65,0:06:07.96,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,从正午的270度\N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}From 270 degrees above zero at mid-day,
Dialogue: 0,0:06:08.27,0:06:12.00,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,到晚上的零下240度 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}to 240 degrees below zero at night.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:17.99,0:06:21.70,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,甚至月球的低引力只有地球的六分之一 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}Even the Moon's low gravity, just one sixth of Earth's,
Dialogue: 0,0:06:21.82,0:06:24.15,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,对旅游者是个冒险的举动 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}could present a hazard to a tourist.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:25.35,0:06:29.03,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,现实中阿波罗宇航员在月球上漫步时\N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}A reality the Apollo astronauts kept at the tops of their minds
Dialogue: 0,0:06:29.14,0:06:31.13,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,要保持了高度的思想集中 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}during their many moonwalks.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:32.58,0:06:35.81,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,他们意识到在他们太空服\N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}They realize that beyond the thickness
Dialogue: 0,0:06:36.08,0:06:39.36,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,的外面是死亡 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}of their visor in their space suit, was death.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:40.98,0:06:43.33,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,他们做事时会被岩石绊倒 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}Should they do something and fall into a rock
Dialogue: 0,0:06:43.42,0:06:45.77,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,失足被露出的岩石击中 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}and lose your footing and fall and hit an outcrop,
Dialogue: 0,0:06:45.95,0:06:48.94,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,面罩会被打碎 把自己暴露在月球的真空里 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}this visor could be cracked, expose you to lunar vacuum,
Dialogue: 0,0:06:49.27,0:06:51.35,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,这样就会是一个严重的情况 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}we would had a serious situation on our hand.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:59.48,0:07:03.79,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,即使太空服可以对付月球的真空 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}But while a spacesuit could protect lunar tourists against the vacuum of space,
Dialogue: 0,0:07:03.90,0:07:08.91,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,月球上缺乏氧气 温度极端 还有致命的太阳辐射 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}a lack of oxygen, temperature extremes, and lethal solar radiation,
Dialogue: 0,0:07:09.83,0:07:13.39,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,但是太空服提供的有限的保护还是无法避免潜在的危险 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}a potential hazard that spacesuit would do little to protect against,
Dialogue: 0,0:07:13.51,0:07:16.62,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,就是高速的微小陨石 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}is high-velocity micro-meteorites.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:18.59,0:07:22.05,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,它们连续打击月球的表面 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}They pummel the lunar surface frequently.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:24.03,0:07:25.73,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,细小的陨石…\NTiny meteorites…
Dialogue: 0,0:07:26.18,0:07:29.55,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,在我们大气层燃烧和产生流星的小陨石 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}The little ones that burn up in our atmosphere and make shooting stars,
Dialogue: 0,0:07:29.64,0:07:33.61,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,那些 月球上没有大气 它们就直接打击表面 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}those, there's no atmosphere on Moon, they're coming right down hitting surface.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:34.73,0:07:37.15,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,它们研磨着月球表面 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}They pulverize the lunar surface,
Dialogue: 0,0:07:37.33,0:07:42.68,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,产生了轻物质的沙尘飞扬 所谓的风化层 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}generating a dusty blanket of gravel light material, called regolith.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:45.12,0:07:50.51,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,阿曼达·汉德里克斯博士在美国航天局的喷气推进实验室里研究月球 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}Doctor Amanda Hendrix studies the moon at NASA's Jet Propulsion Laboratory.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:53.60,0:07:57.32,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,这是普通工厂里的工具 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}This clamp here is kind of a regular factory.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:59.19,0:08:02.21,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,它研磨石块 就是那 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}It's ground up rock, that's what it is.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:04.97,0:08:09.22,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,随着时间推移 研磨会快得多 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}The times goes and this scrubber mill a lot faster.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:10.10,0:08:13.30,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,这至少磨了一个小时了 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}Here it's made in less than an hour,
Dialogue: 0,0:08:13.69,0:08:18.72,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,然而在月球上 已经经历了40亿年的轰击 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}but on the Moon, it is the result of more than four billion years of bombardment,
Dialogue: 0,0:08:18.80,0:08:24.71,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,陨石和小陨石降落在表面 破碎了岩石 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}by meteorites and micro meteorites, raining in on the surface and breaking up the rock.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:26.84,0:08:29.07,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,就象这个研磨机的产物 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}Like the product of this gravel mill,
Dialogue: 0,0:08:29.21,0:08:33.17,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,月球风化层以各种各样的颗粒组成 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}lunar regolith has formed in a variety of grain sizes,
Dialogue: 0,0:08:33.29,0:08:36.55,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,从大石块到细沙 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}from large rocks to fine dust.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:37.99,0:08:42.35,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,这个非常细的沙尘对我们是熟悉的 在来自阿波罗的图象里 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}This very fine dust is familiar to us from Apollo images that
Dialogue: 0,0:08:42.39,0:08:46.19,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,宇航员黄昏的足迹里可以看到 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}were seen of astronaut's footprints in the dusk.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:46.92,0:08:51.27,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,那非常细而且…事实上细到给宇航员造成麻烦 \NIt's very fine and… So fine, in fact, that the astronauts had problems with it.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:51.44,0:08:54.55,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,粘住他们的太空服 进入他们的设备里 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}Sticking to their spacesuits, getting into the equipment
Dialogue: 0,0:08:54.62,0:08:58.18,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,并且最终导致出现一些问题 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}and it can end up causing a bit of a problem.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:01.92,0:09:05.66,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,过去也确实有大的陨石打击月球 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}Really big meteorites have also hit the Moon in the past.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:09.32,0:09:11.54,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,事实上那些大的打击\N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}In fact, these massive impacts
Dialogue: 0,0:09:11.58,0:09:16.01,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,造成了月球上暗的圆形区域 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}are responsible for the dark circular regions on the lunar surface.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:16.30,0:09:18.24,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,许多观察者看到的形状\N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}The shapes that to many observers
Dialogue: 0,0:09:18.31,0:09:23.31,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,象人的眼睛 鼻子和嘴巴那样排列 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}seem to be arranged like the eyes, nose and mouth of a human face.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:24.85,0:09:28.96,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,这使人们对月球产生了幻象 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}They make up the illusion of the man on the moon.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:35.03,0:09:38.16,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,那是月球表面巨大撞击的痕迹 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}They blasted huge basins in the Moon surface.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:38.23,0:09:41.51,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,有些有700英里宽 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}Some of them are 700 miles across.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:45.92,0:09:51.57,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,在撞击的地方黑色的火山岩喷出 充满了盆地 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}Dark lava eventually burst through at the impact points, and flooded the basins.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:57.66,0:10:03.04,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,今 我们把这些暗的区域称为玛丽亚 拉丁文中对海洋的词汇 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}Today, we call these dark regions, maria, the Latin word for seas.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:05.64,0:10:08.03,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,可以追溯到17世纪 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}They states back to the 17th century,
Dialogue: 0,0:10:08.11,0:10:11.83,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,文艺复兴时期的观星者观察月球 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}when Renaissance Era observers looked up at the Moon.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:15.97,0:10:20.19,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,他们推测那些暗区可能是海洋 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}They speculated that the dark areas might be oceans.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:20.55,0:10:26.48,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,那时的天文学家给许多暗的区域或者海洋起了古里古怪的名字 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}And astronomers of the time gave the many dark spots, or seas, whimsical names.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:29.65,0:10:33.48,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,所有海洋被命名的结果曾经作为月球的象征 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}The seas are all named after effects that were once attributed to the Moon.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:33.53,0:10:39.38,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,所以就有了风暴海 危机海 还有宁静海 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}So you have the Sea of Storms and the Sea of Crisis, and the Sea of Tranquility,
Dialogue: 0,0:10:39.52,0:10:41.29,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,以及往前…\Nand so forth…
Dialogue: 0,0:10:43.04,0:10:46.97,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,有些年轻的撞击盆地侵蚀时间较短 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}Some of the younger impact basins have had less time to erode,
Dialogue: 0,0:10:47.28,0:10:50.46,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,所以它们的特性还是比较脆弱 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}so their features are still relatively crisp.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:54.57,0:11:00.06,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,一个细节是叫做东方暗区或者叫东方之海 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}One in particular is called Mare Orientale, or the Eastern Sea.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:00.70,0:11:05.03,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,它有600英里宽 是一次撞击产生的结果 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}It's some 600 miles across, and the impact that created it,
Dialogue: 0,0:11:05.13,0:11:07.05,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,撞击是如此的沉重和直接 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}was so massive and direct.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:07.11,0:11:10.87,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,看上去非常象靶子上公牛的眼睛 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}The result looks very much like the bull's eye on a target.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:13.01,0:11:18.32,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,这个东方之海就象子弹射在玻璃上 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}This Orientale scar is kind of like a bullet shot in the glass, where you see all the
Dialogue: 0,0:11:18.39,0:11:22.19,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,能够看到全部的环状物 碎片喷出来 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}the sort of rings around it and fractures going out.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:25.37,0:11:29.21,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,人们经常说 如果她处在直接对着地球的一面 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}People have often said that if it had been on the side facing directly toward you,
Dialogue: 0,0:11:29.28,0:11:32.07,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,我们就可能会有月球的其它神话了 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}we might have had a whole different mythology about the Moon,
Dialogue: 0,0:11:32.15,0:11:35.50,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,这是因为她就象一个大眼睛注视着我们 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}because it will look like a big eye staring at us.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:43.35,0:11:47.91,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,三个山脉组成的同心环围绕着东方之海 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}Three concentric rings of mountain ranges surround Mare Orientale,
Dialogue: 0,0:11:48.05,0:11:51.97,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,有些山峰高达几千英尺 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}and some of the peaks rise to several thousand feet.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:52.15,0:11:55.50,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,它们是猛烈冲击的产物 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}They're all effects of the monster impact.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:56.91,0:12:03.23,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,当我们在地球上看到环型山 这些首先是由\N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}When we see mountain ranges on the Earth, they're mostly caused first by
Dialogue: 0,0:12:03.35,0:12:08.71,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,周围的陆地运动造成的 陆地相互之间的运动非常缓慢 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}the continents moving around, crashing into each other very slowly, buckling up and
Dialogue: 0,0:12:08.95,0:12:12.21,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,折皱产生环型山 并且在水的侵蚀以后 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}creating mountain ranges which then erode into all that spectacular
Dialogue: 0,0:12:12.28,0:12:16.72,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,才形成我们在马特洪峰看到的壮观景象 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}shapes that we see at the Matterhorn and so forth, from water erosion.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:17.67,0:12:21.28,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,在月球上没有大陆板块运动 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}On the Moon, there are no continental plate tectonics.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:21.47,0:12:23.51,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,表面是静止的 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}The surface is static.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:23.63,0:12:25.94,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,是的 在月球上还是能看到山脉 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}Yeah. You still have mountains on the Moon
Dialogue: 0,0:12:26.14,0:12:30.78,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,原因在于那些巨大的撞击盆地 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}and the reason is that those big impact basins.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:33.52,0:12:36.40,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,那是一个巨大的喷发陷坑 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}That's big explosion excavates a pit,
Dialogue: 0,0:12:36.47,0:12:40.62,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,物体投掷在外面 所以会有环形山 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}throws the material up on the outsides, so you have these rings of mountains,
Dialogue: 0,0:12:40.71,0:12:44.16,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,弧形山包围着撞击的地点 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}arcs of mountains, that surround the impact sites.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:44.43,0:12:47.48,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,然而这些撞击特征是由外部力量引发的 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}But their impact features in there is caused by the external forces,
Dialogue: 0,0:12:47.55,0:12:49.10,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,而不是内部力量引起的 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}not the internal forces.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:50.82,0:12:54.84,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,另一个引人注目的撞击坑 要比东方之海小许多 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}Another notable impact crater, much smaller than Mare Orientale,
Dialogue: 0,0:12:54.93,0:12:58.77,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,但非常壮观 叫第谷 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}but every bit as spectacular, is Tycho.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:00.89,0:13:04.69,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,是以17世纪一位著名的丹麦天文学家的名字命名的 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}Named after a prominent 17th century Danish astronomer,
Dialogue: 0,0:13:04.90,0:13:06.15,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,这个撞击坑\N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}this impact feature
Dialogue: 0,0:13:06.18,0:13:10.46,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,坐落在月球西南方的边缘处 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}is located in the southwestern quadrant on the Moon's near side.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:14.02,0:13:18.02,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,它是…在明亮的区域 用肉眼几乎就能看到它 \NIt's… in the bright area, you could have almost see it with the naked eye.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:22.84,0:13:26.31,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,当它爆发时 就象其它许多弹坑一样 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}And when that explosion happened as with many other craters
Dialogue: 0,0:13:26.35,0:13:30.06,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,喷射出明亮的粉尘 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}it shot out jets of bright powdery dust,
Dialogue: 0,0:13:30.15,0:13:34.06,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,所以这些喷发的放射状条纹很清楚 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}so that these rays that got out from it were very stripy.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:34.55,0:13:41.71,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,喷射出来的放射状物质从第谷的碰撞点向外延展了900英里 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}The rays of dusty ejected material extends some 900 miles from the Tycho impact site.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:43.07,0:13:47.04,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,一座残留的山体也在弹坑的中心升起 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}A mountain of debris also rises from the center of the crater.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:47.34,0:13:50.55,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,这是小行星撞击的反作用力造成的 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}This is a result of recoil from the asteroid's strike.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:50.94,0:13:54.53,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,在那个撞击点中心的一些被高速压扁的物质\N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}Some of the highly compressed material at the center of the impact site
Dialogue: 0,0:13:54.61,0:14:00.43,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,向外弹出 一旦撞击 要么弹起 要么粉碎 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}springs outward, once the impacting body either ricochets or disintegrates.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:04.16,0:14:07.57,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,然而长期以来所有的月球特征\N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}But long before any of the Moon specific features
Dialogue: 0,0:14:07.65,0:14:11.48,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,都已经通过望远镜和太空旅行了解清楚了 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}could be discern through sophisticated telescopes and space travel,
Dialogue: 0,0:14:11.73,0:14:14.86,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,对月球的外貌和举止行为的仔细观察\N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}careful observation of the lunar behavior and appearance
Dialogue: 0,0:14:14.99,0:14:18.26,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,对地球的居民来说仍然是至关重要的 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}was still vitally important to Earth dwellers.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:33.03,0:14:38.66,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,至少在15000年里 人类敬仰月亮作为光的来源 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}For 15,000 years at least, Man revered the Moon as a source of light,
Dialogue: 0,0:14:39.67,0:14:41.64,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,作为航海的指南 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}as a navigational guide,
Dialogue: 0,0:14:42.46,0:14:45.25,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,作为农业生产的参考 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}as a reference in agricultural pursuits.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:46.97,0:14:50.97,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,而最重要的是…作为方便的计时器 \NAnd most of all… as a convenient timekeeper.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:53.32,0:14:58.22,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,在现代社会之前的日子里 计时可不是件容易的事 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}In the days before our modern systems, timekeeping was no simple task.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:00.24,0:15:02.79,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,早期的计时有两种选择 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}Early timekeepers had two choices:
Dialogue: 0,0:15:03.32,0:15:06.57,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,依靠太阳或者月亮 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}they could monitor the Sun or the Moon.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:06.99,0:15:10.50,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,如果你想记录日期 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}If you think about trying to keep track of dates,
Dialogue: 0,0:15:10.80,0:15:13.89,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,如果你用我们现在使用的阳历计时 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}if you use a solar calendar like we do nowadays,
Dialogue: 0,0:15:13.96,0:15:18.53,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,一年就有365天 那就要持续记录大量的天数 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}there are 365 days in a year, and that's an awful lot of days to keep track of,
Dialogue: 0,0:15:18.81,0:15:22.71,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,这是一件平常人难以做好的事情 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}and it's not something that the ordinary person could do very well.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:25.78,0:15:30.08,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,相对的是用阴历 谁都会告诉你月亮什么时候处在满月 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}Compare that with a lunar calendar. Everybody can tell when the full moon is
Dialogue: 0,0:15:30.19,0:15:32.87,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,月亮什么时候处在新月 用不着看月亮是不是新月 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}when the new moon is, you don't see the moon at new moon,
Dialogue: 0,0:15:32.95,0:15:35.92,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,只要将月亮与满月做个比较很容易就告诉你了 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}you see it as big and round at full moon so it's easy to tell,
Dialogue: 0,0:15:36.16,0:15:40.75,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,月亮的周期只有28或29天 很容易计算 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}there are only 28 or 29 days in a lunar cycle, so it's easy to count them
Dialogue: 0,0:15:40.92,0:15:44.75,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,所以大多数民族还是用阴历的 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}and so most societies actually started out with a lunar calendar.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:49.16,0:15:53.20,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,早期的月球观察家也承认那颗我们星球的伙伴\N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}Early observers of the Moon also recognize that our planetary neighbor
Dialogue: 0,0:15:53.22,0:15:56.52,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,对地球有着非常的物理作用 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}has a very real physical effect on the Earth itself.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:58.78,0:16:03.03,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,月球与我们的海洋的潮汐涨落有关 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}The Moon is responsible for the rise and fall of our ocean tides.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:07.94,0:16:10.37,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,如果月球是这个网球 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}If I think of the Moon as being this tennis ball
Dialogue: 0,0:16:10.45,0:16:12.89,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,地球是这个足球 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}and the Earth as being this football,
Dialogue: 0,0:16:13.16,0:16:16.98,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,潮汐是由月球的引力引起的 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}the tides are caused by the Moon's gravitational attraction,
Dialogue: 0,0:16:17.23,0:16:22.26,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,这是显而易见的…这样 月球的力量牵引着地球上的水 \Nso it's obvious… Ok, so the Moon kind of pulls the Earth's water towards it.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:28.08,0:16:31.50,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,所以这造成了朝着月球的方向稍微有些隆起 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}And so this creates a slight bulge in the direction of the Moon.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:31.92,0:16:35.48,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,同样在背对月球方向的地方也稍微有些隆起 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}Well, it's less obvious that there's also a bulge in the direction away from the Moon,
Dialogue: 0,0:16:35.55,0:16:38.27,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,这事实上就是每天两次高潮的原因 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}so there is in fact two high tides every day.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:41.87,0:16:43.99,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,其它高潮你能够想象到是由\N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}The other high tide you can think of is being caused
Dialogue: 0,0:16:44.04,0:16:46.09,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,地球的向心力引起的 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}by the Earth's centripetal force.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:47.01,0:16:50.27,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,地球和月球两者轮流运转 引起\N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}The Earth and the Moon are both rotating around, and that causes
Dialogue: 0,0:16:50.35,0:16:53.43,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,远处的水同样运动 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}the water on the far side to also move out.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:56.18,0:17:00.07,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,涨潮和落潮之间差异的一个极端的例子\N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}An extreme illustration of the difference between high and low tides
Dialogue: 0,0:17:00.16,0:17:03.82,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,可以在加拿大芬迪湾看到 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}can be found along the shore of Canada's Bay of Fundy.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:05.99,0:17:08.62,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,涨潮和落潮之间的落差\N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}The water level from high tide to low tide
Dialogue: 0,0:17:08.66,0:17:11.37,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,竟然达到55英尺 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}drops an astounding 55 feet.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:13.94,0:17:16.22,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,对地球上的某些生命来说 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}For some forms of life on Earth,
Dialogue: 0,0:17:16.51,0:17:20.76,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,涨潮和落潮创造了有益的环境 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}the advance and retreat of the tides creates useful habitats.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:26.92,0:17:30.13,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,然而月球对我们星球的另一个引力作用 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}But another of the Moon's gravitational effect on our planet
Dialogue: 0,0:17:30.21,0:17:36.83,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,是直接作用陆地生存的生命 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}is directly responsible for nothing less than the continued survival of terrestrial life itself.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:38.42,0:17:43.14,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,月球稳定地球的气候 月球的引力\N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}The Moon stabilizes Earth's climate. The gravitational effect of the Moon
Dialogue: 0,0:17:43.21,0:17:47.03,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,使得地球的自转轴倾斜保持在一定的角度 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}keeps the degree of tilt on the Earth's rotational axis constant.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:47.44,0:17:51.22,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,这个倾斜保持了季节的周期 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}This tilt is what maintains the repeatable cycle of seasons,
Dialogue: 0,0:17:51.31,0:17:53.59,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,随着地球围绕太阳运转 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}as the Earth orbits the Sun.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:54.84,0:17:59.92,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,如果我们没有月球 如果我们没有一个小许多的月球 举个例子 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}If we didn't have the Moon, or if we had a much smaller Moon, for example,
Dialogue: 0,0:18:01.10,0:18:03.75,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,可以通过计算看出 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}then you can mathematically show,
Dialogue: 0,0:18:03.95,0:18:08.64,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,我们的北极的倾斜会有很大差别 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}that the tilt of our north pole would vary widely,
Dialogue: 0,0:18:09.74,0:18:14.98,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,换角度来说从0到90度 现在是23.5度 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}with that angle going, from, say, 0 to 90 degrees, currently it's 23.5 degrees,
Dialogue: 0,0:18:15.60,0:18:17.67,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,事实上那将会很混乱 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}and it would actually vary chaotically.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:18.39,0:18:24.00,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,所以月球在稳定我们的旋转轴 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}And so the Moon has played an important role in the stability
Dialogue: 0,0:18:24.08,0:18:28.03,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,稳定我们星球和气候方面扮演了重要的角色 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}of our axis of rotation, of our planet and therefore in our climate.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:32.72,0:18:35.38,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,在过去的年代里 由于月球\N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}Over the millennia, with the Moon's prominent
Dialogue: 0,0:18:35.45,0:18:38.12,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,始终如一地挂在天空 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}and constant presence in our night sky,
Dialogue: 0,0:18:39.33,0:18:42.97,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,人们终于开始推测她的来历 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}man ultimately began to speculate on its origin.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:44.47,0:18:48.39,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,她是如何形成的？月球是怎么来的？\N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}How did it form? How did the Moon come to be?
Dialogue: 0,0:18:50.47,0:18:54.56,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,公元前455年 希腊学者 安那克萨哥拉\N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}In 455 BCE the Greek scholar Anaxagoras
Dialogue: 0,0:18:54.64,0:18:59.27,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,推断月球只是地球甩出去的一块石头 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}theorized that the Moon was simply a rock that was flung off by the Earth.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:01.09,0:19:03.55,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,而此时大多数他的同时代的人\N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}Most of his contemporaries, on the other hand,
Dialogue: 0,0:19:03.64,0:19:06.54,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,却深信月球是神灵 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}were convinced that the Moon was a god,
Dialogue: 0,0:19:07.00,0:19:09.22,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,或可能是个巨大的火球 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}or maybe a huge ball of fire.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:09.94,0:19:13.48,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,所以 安那克萨哥拉 的想法没有得到更多的关注 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}So Anaxagoras' notion did not get much attraction.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:14.68,0:19:17.24,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,冷静的思考毫无疑问还在继续 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}Quiet speculation no doubt continued,
Dialogue: 0,0:19:17.31,0:19:21.68,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,但一直到1609年都还没有过硬的说法 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}but no hard information about the Moon came until 1609.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:23.88,0:19:26.65,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,当意大利天文学家伽利略\N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}When Italian astronomer Galileo Galilei
Dialogue: 0,0:19:26.68,0:19:29.44,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,首次用望远镜对准月球时 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}pointed one of the first telescopes at the Moon,
Dialogue: 0,0:19:29.49,0:19:34.60,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,验证了他所看到的景观是另一个世界的地形 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}recognized that he was looking at a landscape, the terrain of another world.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:37.67,0:19:39.82,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,当你通过望远镜观看月球 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}When you look at the Moon through a telescope,
Dialogue: 0,0:19:39.87,0:19:43.12,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,看到情况与肉眼看到完全不同 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}it looks completely different from the way it looks to the naked eye.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:43.57,0:19:46.33,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,所以肉眼看到的平坦的景象被替代了 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}So instead of looking flat the way it does to the naked eye,
Dialogue: 0,0:19:46.44,0:19:49.04,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,环望四周 都是阴影 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}it really looks round, and you can see the shadows,
Dialogue: 0,0:19:49.11,0:19:52.44,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,看到的都是弹坑 肉眼是看不到的 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}you can see all these craters that a naked eye just not see,
Dialogue: 0,0:19:52.54,0:19:54.87,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,只是一眼看上去象个宇宙 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}and it just immediately looks like a world,
Dialogue: 0,0:19:54.92,0:19:57.47,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,从三维世界里跳了出来 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}it jumps out at you into three dimensions.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:59.53,0:20:03.40,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,伽利略详细地描绘了小行星的表面 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}Galileo made detailed drawings of the small planet's surface,
Dialogue: 0,0:20:03.69,0:20:07.83,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,并且永远确立了月球是固体的星球 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}and established once and for all that the Moon is a solid world,
Dialogue: 0,0:20:08.15,0:20:10.80,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,不是神灵或火球 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}not a god or a fireball.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:13.41,0:20:18.12,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,然而这位天文开拓者从未公开推测月球的起源 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}But the groundbreaking astronomer never publicly speculated on the Moon's origin.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:18.32,0:20:22.11,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,首先是因为他假设那是颗其它的行星 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}Primarily because he hasn't assume move to other planets.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:24.99,0:20:27.30,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,不过直到1873年 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}Not until 1873
Dialogue: 0,0:20:27.55,0:20:31.33,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,关于月球起源的科学理论才\N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}did the first science based theory regarding the origin of the Moon
Dialogue: 0,0:20:31.42,0:20:33.04,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,首次公开发表 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}publicly emerge.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:33.81,0:20:38.68,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,是从天才的法国天文学家爱德华·洛希头脑里涌现出来 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}It sprang from the mind of a talented French astronomer named Edouard Roche.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:39.07,0:20:42.48,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,洛希鼓吹所谓的共同成长理论 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}Roche advocated for what's called the co-accretion theory,
Dialogue: 0,0:20:42.68,0:20:44.68,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,那主要是表明 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}which says that basically
Dialogue: 0,0:20:44.74,0:20:49.14,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,地球和月球是在同一时间形成 由相同物质组成的 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}Earth and the Moon grew up at the same time, out of the same materials.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:52.38,0:20:56.07,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,那时许多科学家开始相信\N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}In Roche's days many scientists began to believe
Dialogue: 0,0:20:56.27,0:21:01.04,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,行星是由冷凝的气体云形成的 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}that the planets might have formed from hot condensing clouds of gas.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:06.30,0:21:09.63,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,它逐渐收缩冷却 并且随着收缩 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}It gradually contracted and cooled and as it contracted,
Dialogue: 0,0:21:09.72,0:21:12.37,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,分离气体环 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}it would separate out rings of gas, so you'd have
Dialogue: 0,0:21:12.42,0:21:15.48,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,所以气体环在这里 一个环在这里 等等 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}a ring of gas here, a ring here and so forth.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:15.61,0:21:20.25,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,这些气体环最后终于凝结形成行星 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}And these rings of gas would then eventually coalesce and form the planets.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:23.53,0:21:27.16,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,洛希说地球和月球是太阳系的缩影 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}Roche saw the Earth and the Moon as a solar system in miniature.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:27.17,0:21:30.69,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,他的想法是地球开始时是个气体球 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}His idea was that the Earth starts out as a ball of gas
Dialogue: 0,0:21:30.69,0:21:34.31,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,在冷却收缩时散发出气体环 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}and then cools and contracts and sheds a ring of gas,
Dialogue: 0,0:21:34.31,0:21:37.74,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,然后环自身粘合形成月球 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}that then itself coalesces and forms the Moon.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:48.32,0:21:50.83,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,然而这个理论有问题 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}But there are problems with this theory.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:52.19,0:21:57.01,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,一个问题是月球的铁含量要比地球的铁含量小得多 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}For one our Moon has a much lower iron content than the Earth.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:57.52,0:22:00.30,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,如果两者是相同的物质组成的 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}If the two bodies formed from the same materials,
Dialogue: 0,0:22:00.40,0:22:02.91,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,那么它们的基本成分应该是一致的 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}their basic composition should be the same.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:02.96,0:22:04.46,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,但是两者却不相同 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}But they are not.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:04.46,0:22:06.59,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,相互之间的矛盾\N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}This and other inconsistencies
Dialogue: 0,0:22:06.59,0:22:10.19,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,很快就引导天文学家寻求新的思路\N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}soon led fellow astronomers to quest for new ideas
Dialogue: 0,0:22:10.19,0:22:13.43,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,去解释月球的存在 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}to explain the existence of the Moon.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:20.22,0:22:23.15,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,在19世纪最后的三分之一时期内 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}In the last third of the 19's century
Dialogue: 0,0:22:23.35,0:22:28.39,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,关于月球起源的先进理论开始出现 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}advanced theories about the origin of the Moon started to emerge.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:29.43,0:22:33.27,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,1873年法国科学家爱德华·洛希\N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}In 1873 French scientist, Edouard Roche
Dialogue: 0,0:22:33.27,0:22:36.45,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,提出月球只是在地球旁边形成的 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}proposed that the Moon simply formed alongside the Earth
Dialogue: 0,0:22:36.45,0:22:40.44,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,本质上是由相同的粒子和气体的星云构成的 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}out of essentially the same nebular cloud of particles and gasses.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:42.28,0:22:45.41,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,但是这个主张有基本的弱点 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}But this idea had a fundamental weakness.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:45.93,0:22:49.65,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,月球的铁含量比地球低得多 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}The Moon has a much lower iron content that the Earth.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:50.05,0:22:52.40,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,密度小许多 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}It's much less dense.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:55.70,0:22:58.96,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,让我们想起月球和她的成分的要紧的事情是\N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}The big thing that we remember about the Moon and its composition is
Dialogue: 0,0:22:58.96,0:23:02.33,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,她没有地球一样的铁核 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}that it doesn't have any iron core like the Earth does.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:03.37,0:23:07.07,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,所以你看 地球有个非常大的核心 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}So you look at the Earth, and there is a very large central area
Dialogue: 0,0:23:07.07,0:23:11.34,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,地球重的内部是铁 镍-铁 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}something like hefty inside of the Earth is iron, nickel-iron
Dialogue: 0,0:23:11.49,0:23:14.85,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,金属流向地球的核心 在那 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}and that's metal of drain down to the center of the Earth in there.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:14.85,0:23:17.20,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,地球开始形成时是热的 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}Earth was hot when it formed at the beginning.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:17.87,0:23:19.73,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,月球更多地只是象普通的石块 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}The Moon is more like just plain rock.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:24.23,0:23:27.25,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,科学家最初推断月球的质量\N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}Scientists initially deduce the mass of the Moon
Dialogue: 0,0:23:27.29,0:23:30.32,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,是通过观察和数学计算 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}through observation and mathematical calculations.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:33.61,0:23:36.93,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,如果月球是由与地球相同的物质形成的 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}If the Moon had formed from the same stuff that made the Earth,
Dialogue: 0,0:23:36.93,0:23:39.34,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,那铁的含量应该是相似的 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}the iron content should be similar.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:40.61,0:23:44.81,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,这是爱德华·洛希无法解释的理论上的漏洞 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}It was a hole in the theory Edouard Roche couldn't explain.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:45.42,0:23:48.26,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,但是另一个想法随着\N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}But another idea soon followed down the hills
Dialogue: 0,0:23:48.26,0:23:50.71,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,共同成长的假设而来 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}of the co-accretion hypothesis.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:51.38,0:23:57.53,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,1878年乔治·达尔文宣布了他的月球起源的裂变理论 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}In 1878 George Darwin announced his fission theory of lunar origin.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:04.61,0:24:10.21,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,这个理论受到了部分人的关注 因为达尔文有个著名的老爸 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}This idea received some attention in part because Darwin had a celebrated father,
Dialogue: 0,0:24:10.93,0:24:14.54,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,查尔斯·罗伯特·达尔文--的作者 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}Charles Darwin, author of "Origin of Species".
Dialogue: 0,0:24:15.15,0:24:19.08,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,乔治·达尔文及时摆脱了老爸的影子 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}In time though, George Darwin stepped out of this father shadow
Dialogue: 0,0:24:19.08,0:24:23.08,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,成为了英国著名的潮汐学领军专家 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}and became known as England's leading expert on tides.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:23.76,0:24:27.42,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,通过广泛分析潮汐-月球的关系 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}And through extensive analysis of the tide-moon relationship
Dialogue: 0,0:24:27.43,0:24:30.06,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,乔治·达尔文认识到\N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}George Darwin came to the realization
Dialogue: 0,0:24:30.06,0:24:34.78,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,月球正逐渐地越来越远离地球 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}that the moon is gradually moving further and further away from the Earth.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:35.39,0:24:38.58,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,这在95年后被证实了 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}It wasn't proved until 95 years later.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:38.68,0:24:40.64,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,在宇航员登陆月球时 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}When astronauts landed on the moon,
Dialogue: 0,0:24:40.64,0:24:43.60,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,在月球上安放了一面小镜子 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}they put little mirrors on the moon.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:47.17,0:24:48.99,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,可以将一束激光射向月球 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}And you can shine a laser at the Moon
Dialogue: 0,0:24:49.10,0:24:51.52,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,镜子将激光反射回来 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}and the laser rebounds at the mirror come back
Dialogue: 0,0:24:51.62,0:24:55.27,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,实际上这能够精确地测量地球和月球之间的距离 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}and you can actually measure the exact distance between the Earth and the Moon.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:56.28,0:25:01.22,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,地月之间的距离正以每年3.8厘米的速度分开 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}And the rate at which this distance is increasing is 3.8 cm/year.
Dialogue: 0,0:25:02.12,0:25:05.68,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,3.8厘米是1.5英寸 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}3.8 cm is about an inch and a half.
Dialogue: 0,0:25:05.68,0:25:08.12,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,如果做一个动画来表示的话 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}If you made a movie extreme timate,
Dialogue: 0,0:25:08.12,0:25:10.87,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,就会看到月球逐渐地远离地球 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}you will see the Moon moving away from Earth gradually.
Dialogue: 0,0:25:10.87,0:25:12.62,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,这就是我们现在所看到的 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}That's what we see nowadays.
Dialogue: 0,0:25:20.14,0:25:24.90,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,达尔文开始考虑时间往后推将会发生什么 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}Darwin began to consider what would happen if we reverse the process,
Dialogue: 0,0:25:24.90,0:25:27.67,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,把动画往后倒转 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}if you run the movie backwards.
Dialogue: 0,0:25:30.03,0:25:34.12,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,当我们把时间倒转 月球逐步靠近 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}As we move backwards in time, and the Moon moves closer,
Dialogue: 0,0:25:34.13,0:25:36.99,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,月球的运转和地球的运转\N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}both the Moon's orbit and the rotation of the Earth
Dialogue: 0,0:25:37.09,0:25:39.44,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,越来越快 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}get faster and faster.
Dialogue: 0,0:25:41.84,0:25:45.05,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,所以当月球最终与地球融合时会发生什么 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}And so what will happen if then eventually the Moon must
Dialogue: 0,0:25:45.05,0:25:47.92,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,必须要考虑到地球 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}coalesce with the Earth, and must, must take the Earth.
Dialogue: 0,0:25:49.22,0:25:51.38,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,达尔文对此合乎逻辑的结论是 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}The logical conclusion for Darwin
Dialogue: 0,0:25:51.49,0:25:54.76,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,快速旋转的地球融化的一部分\N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}was that a portion of the molten rapidly spinning Earth
Dialogue: 0,0:25:54.77,0:25:57.15,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,必定是与主体分离出来 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}must have separated from the main mass
Dialogue: 0,0:25:57.15,0:26:00.39,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,产生了我们的月亮 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}and spawn off to become our Moon.
Dialogue: 0,0:26:06.02,0:26:09.53,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,他立即进行数学计算 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}He immediately began work on mathematical calculations
Dialogue: 0,0:26:09.63,0:26:11.73,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,逆转月球的轨道\N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}to reverse the trajectory of the Moon
Dialogue: 0,0:26:11.73,0:26:14.08,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,完全回到地球为止 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}all the way back to the Earth.
Dialogue: 0,0:26:14.08,0:26:17.59,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,令人沮丧的是他几乎得到了回到地球的那个点 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}Frustratingly, he reaches a point where he gets almost to Earth
Dialogue: 0,0:26:17.69,0:26:20.07,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,然而接着却无法更进一步进行下去 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}and then he couldn't work it out any further.
Dialogue: 0,0:26:20.08,0:26:22.33,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,数学无法更进一步进行下去 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}The mathematic doesn't let you go any further.
Dialogue: 0,0:26:22.33,0:26:24.48,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,得到的结果是月球\N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}What you get to as a point where the Moon is
Dialogue: 0,0:26:24.48,0:26:27.80,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,围绕着地球急速旋转 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}whipping around the Earth at a rate of
Dialogue: 0,0:26:27.90,0:26:31.47,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,速度达到每天5圈或6圈 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}five revolutions a day or six revolutions a day.
Dialogue: 0,0:26:31.47,0:26:34.42,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,所以 她只是…围绕地球急速移动 \NSo, it's just… zooming around the Earth.
Dialogue: 0,0:26:34.42,0:26:36.73,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,是啊 她..在大约\NOk? And it's… it's about
Dialogue: 0,0:26:36.83,0:26:39.58,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,距离地球5000英里的地方 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}5,000 miles away from the Earth.
Dialogue: 0,0:26:40.94,0:26:43.37,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,数学仍然无法承认达尔文\N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}Still the mathematics did not allowed Darwin
Dialogue: 0,0:26:43.37,0:26:46.80,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,把两个宇宙天体结合在一起 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}to bring the two cosmic bodies into contact.
Dialogue: 0,0:26:49.63,0:26:52.47,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,分裂理论争论了数十年 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}The fission theory was debated for decades,
Dialogue: 0,0:26:52.58,0:26:54.86,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,但是科学家最后认定\N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}but scientists eventually concluded
Dialogue: 0,0:26:54.96,0:26:57.58,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,地球与月球之间的相对运动\N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}that the relative movements of the Earth and Moon
Dialogue: 0,0:26:57.58,0:26:59.79,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,不是由此造成的 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}could not have resulted from it.
Dialogue: 0,0:27:02.46,0:27:04.68,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,地球旋转得太快 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}The Earth would have be spinning too fast
Dialogue: 0,0:27:04.68,0:27:07.29,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,以至于无法计算出现在的旋转速度 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}to account for its present rotation rate.
Dialogue: 0,0:27:11.93,0:27:15.82,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,继续寻求月球诞生的解释 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}The quest for an explanation of lunar creation continued
Dialogue: 0,0:27:15.82,0:27:19.67,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,不久一个新的理论由一位美国人提出了 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}and a new theory would soon originate with an American.
Dialogue: 0,0:27:23.93,0:27:27.59,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,1909年 托马斯·杰佛逊·杰克逊·希--\N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}In 1909 Thomas Jefferson Jackson See
Dialogue: 0,0:27:27.59,0:27:29.35,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,美国海军上校 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}was a U.S. naval captain
Dialogue: 0,0:27:29.36,0:27:32.28,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,驻扎在旧金山附近的麦尔岛 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}based at Mare Island near San Francisco.
Dialogue: 0,0:27:33.79,0:27:38.83,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,他的官方工作是建立美国西海岸的标准时间 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}His official job was to keep the standard time for the U.S. west coast.
Dialogue: 0,0:27:41.33,0:27:44.28,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,同时杰克逊·希也是位天才的科学家 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}But See was also a gifted scientist.
Dialogue: 0,0:27:44.38,0:27:47.79,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,作为年轻人 他被培养成为天文学家 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}As a young man he had trained as an astronomer.
Dialogue: 0,0:27:47.89,0:27:53.00,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,他是美国首位天文学博士 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}He was one of the first Americans to actually get a doctorate in astronomy.
Dialogue: 0,0:27:53.00,0:27:56.11,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,他去过德国并得到天文学哲学博士 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}He went to Germany and got a Ph.D. in astronomy
Dialogue: 0,0:27:56.21,0:27:59.61,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,那个 你知道吗 那时几乎闻所未闻 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}which was, you know, almost unheard of back then.
Dialogue: 0,0:27:59.81,0:28:04.72,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,在19世纪 美国的科学还是死水一潭 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}The U.S. was still scientifically total backwater in the 1800s.
Dialogue: 0,0:28:05.47,0:28:09.50,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,杰克逊·希的驻扎地麦尔岛有座天文台 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}See's duty station, Mare Island, had an observatory.
Dialogue: 0,0:28:09.92,0:28:14.33,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,上校的工作有着充裕的时间去探讨理论 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}And the captain's job allowed him plenty of time to theorize.
Dialogue: 0,0:28:16.39,0:28:21.55,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,他用尽了时间去探讨共同成长和分裂假设\N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}He had spent time analyzing both the co-accretion and the fission hypothesis
Dialogue: 0,0:28:21.56,0:28:23.70,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,这两个月球诞生的理论 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}regarding the origin of the Moon,
Dialogue: 0,0:28:24.10,0:28:26.29,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,他不相信这些理论 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}and he wasn't convinced.
Dialogue: 0,0:28:26.95,0:28:31.06,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,托马斯·希逐步地发展了截然不同的概念 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}Gradually Thomas See developed a completely different idea.
Dialogue: 0,0:28:31.36,0:28:34.55,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,这个概念被称为"捕获理论" \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}It came to be called "the capture theory".
Dialogue: 0,0:28:37.53,0:28:41.35,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,托马斯·希的理论在本质上表明月球实际形成\N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}Essentially See theorized that the Moon had actually formed
Dialogue: 0,0:28:41.36,0:28:44.33,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,在太阳系里与地球不同的地方 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}in a different part of the solar system from the Earth
Dialogue: 0,0:28:44.33,0:28:48.04,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,它围绕着太阳运转 就象颗其它的行星 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}that it orbited the Sun just like the other planets.
Dialogue: 0,0:28:48.27,0:28:51.71,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,但是它有些地方太靠近地球 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}But that at some point it had moved too close to Earth
Dialogue: 0,0:28:51.81,0:28:54.48,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,并被地球的引力所捕获 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}and was captured by Earth's gravity.
Dialogue: 0,0:28:58.21,0:29:01.64,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,他提出在外太空存在他称之为阻尼介质的东西 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}His idea was that there is something that he called the resisting medium
Dialogue: 0,0:29:01.68,0:29:04.33,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,其实我们现在知道那并不存在 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}in outer space, which we know is not there now.
Dialogue: 0,0:29:05.50,0:29:10.15,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,托马斯·希从来没有充分解释假设的阻尼介质\N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}See never adequately explained what this resisting medium was supposed to be
Dialogue: 0,0:29:10.60,0:29:12.79,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,是不是细小的物质粒子 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}possibly tiny particles of matter.
Dialogue: 0,0:29:13.32,0:29:16.51,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,不管怎样他肯定那已经不复存在 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}Regardless he was sure that no longer existed.
Dialogue: 0,0:29:18.90,0:29:21.76,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,他的概念是地球捕获了月球 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}His idea is that for the Earth to capture the Moon
Dialogue: 0,0:29:21.82,0:29:24.57,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,月球是来自远方 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}the Moon would have to come in from far away
Dialogue: 0,0:29:24.61,0:29:28.60,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,接着他碰到了所谓的阻尼介质慢慢下降 接着\N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}and then it would hit this resisting medium and slow down and then
Dialogue: 0,0:29:28.85,0:29:30.62,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,逐渐被捕获进入轨道 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}gradually get captured into an orbit,
Dialogue: 0,0:29:30.66,0:29:32.65,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,可能不是一次 可能有一小段时间\N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}maybe not at once, it may take a little while
Dialogue: 0,0:29:32.98,0:29:35.59,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,逐渐被捕获进入地球的势力范围 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}to get gradually be captured into Earth orbit.
Dialogue: 0,0:29:36.37,0:29:41.35,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,所以这就象悬崖弹跳者跳跃大桥 下去 上来 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}So it'd be like a bungee jumper jumping off a bridge, they go down, come back up
Dialogue: 0,0:29:41.47,0:29:43.94,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,近距离的下去上来 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}not quite as far go down, come back up.
Dialogue: 0,0:29:51.45,0:29:54.33,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,最后终于下降到底部 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}Then eventually they settle down at the bottom.
Dialogue: 0,0:29:55.35,0:29:58.79,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,托马斯·希的捕获理论的确解释了\N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}Thomas See's capture theory would certainly explain the difference
Dialogue: 0,0:29:58.81,0:30:01.37,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,地球与月球两者铁核的不同 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}in iron content between the Earth and the Moon.
Dialogue: 0,0:30:01.80,0:30:05.77,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,如果月球是在其它地方形成的 那她的成分就会有很大的不同 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}If the Moon formed elsewhere its composition could be very different.
Dialogue: 0,0:30:07.58,0:30:11.59,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,另一方面所谓的地球引力捕获和保留\N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}On the other hand the notion that Earth gravity could capture and retain
Dialogue: 0,0:30:11.65,0:30:13.91,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,如此大的物体是不可能的 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}such a large object was unlikely,
Dialogue: 0,0:30:14.27,0:30:16.57,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,这是因为显然没有阻尼介质\N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}since there is no obvious resisting medium
Dialogue: 0,0:30:16.62,0:30:19.46,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,把月球这么大的物体的速度降下来 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}to slows down an object as big as the Moon.
Dialogue: 0,0:30:21.80,0:30:24.96,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,所有三个理论都有着重大的弱点 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}All three theories have significant weaknesses.
Dialogue: 0,0:30:26.57,0:30:30.09,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,月球的起源保持着神秘 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}The origin of the Moon remained a mystery.
Dialogue: 0,0:30:37.21,0:30:44.49,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,1969年7月20日 美国宇航员首次踏足月球表面 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}On July 20th 1969 US astronauts set foot on the lunar surface for the first time.
Dialogue: 0,0:30:45.71,0:30:48.39,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,这是人的一小步 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}That's one small step for man,
Dialogue: 0,0:30:49.18,0:30:52.03,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,却是人类的一大步 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}one giant leap for mankind.
Dialogue: 0,0:30:52.96,0:30:56.26,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,他们的登月舱登陆在坚硬的火山岩平原 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}They had landed their lunar module on hardened lava plain
Dialogue: 0,0:30:56.31,0:30:58.40,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,那里叫做宁静海 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}known as the Sea of Tranquility.
Dialogue: 0,0:31:00.80,0:31:06.25,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,宇航员巴兹·奥尔德林描述了看到的广阔荒凉的景象 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}And mission pilot Buzz Aldrin described the view as magnificent desolation.
Dialogue: 0,0:31:06.48,0:31:08.66,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,-美极了…-有什么东西吗？\N- Beautiful view… - Isn't that something?
Dialogue: 0,0:31:08.73,0:31:10.51,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,下面的景色好宏伟 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}Magnificent sight down here.
Dialogue: 0,0:31:12.23,0:31:16.94,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,宇航员带回了48磅月球的岩石和土壤 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}The astronauts brought back 48 pounds of moon rocks and dusty soil,
Dialogue: 0,0:31:17.14,0:31:18.25,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,或风化层 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}or regolith.
Dialogue: 0,0:31:20.60,0:31:27.65,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,大声清晰地读出你的位置 我们的位置在133 0-69 15 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}Reading you loud and clear. Our position 133:0-69:15.
Dialogue: 0,0:31:27.79,0:31:32.51,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,休斯敦约翰逊航天中心的地质学家急切地等候着他们的归来 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}Geologist at Johnson Space Center in Houston eagerly awaited their arrival.
Dialogue: 0,0:31:40.93,0:31:43.61,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,样本第一次被带回的刺激就象触电一样 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}The excitement when samples first came back was just electrical.
Dialogue: 0,0:31:43.65,0:31:45.17,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,我的意思是 这真是难以置信 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}I mean, it was just incredible.
Dialogue: 0,0:31:45.23,0:31:47.76,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,没有人真的完全知道自己所期待的 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}Nobody really knew quite what to expect.
Dialogue: 0,0:31:53.87,0:31:57.77,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,我们立即意识到这块玄武岩\N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}And we realized right away that we had basaltic rocks
Dialogue: 0,0:31:58.02,0:32:00.48,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,就象夏威夷可能会看到的 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}like one might see in Hawaii.
Dialogue: 0,0:32:01.74,0:32:04.93,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,事实上非常象会在夏威夷看到的石头 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}In fact very similar to rocks one would see in Hawaii.
Dialogue: 0,0:32:06.23,0:32:10.01,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,美国航天局的地质学家私下希望看到的不仅仅是玄武岩 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}The NASA geologist were intrigued to find not only basalts
Dialogue: 0,0:32:10.09,0:32:11.95,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,而是另外一种石头 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}but rocks of another sort.
Dialogue: 0,0:32:13.58,0:32:15.82,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,石头叫角砾岩 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}Rocks called breccias.
Dialogue: 0,0:32:17.31,0:32:20.09,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,角砾岩形成于小行星撞击 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}Breccias form during asteroid impacts.
Dialogue: 0,0:32:24.41,0:32:27.37,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,所以你能想象如果一个巨大的物体撞击月球 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}So if you can imagine a large impact body hitting the Moon it's gonna be
Dialogue: 0,0:32:27.40,0:32:32.13,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,将会非常混乱 将会撞出碎片 碎片将会飞起 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}very chaotic, it's gonna throw up debris. Debris gonna come flying out this what
Dialogue: 0,0:32:32.29,0:32:36.77,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,形成弹坑 结束后 在月球上看到许多弹坑 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}ends up to be a crater after it's over and you can see the many craters on the Moon.
Dialogue: 0,0:32:39.67,0:32:43.61,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,碎片乱七八糟地堆积在弹坑的四周 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}This debris gets all jumbled up and lands on the ground around the crater
Dialogue: 0,0:32:43.71,0:32:46.19,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,接着碎片会由弹坑产生的热融合在一起 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}and then it gets compacted with the heat generated by the crater
Dialogue: 0,0:32:46.24,0:32:49.13,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,转化成岩石 看起来非常混乱 你瞧 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}and gets turned into rocks that look very chaotic, you see.
Dialogue: 0,0:32:49.20,0:32:51.91,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,石头里各种碎片有不同的大小 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}All sorts of pieces in the rock in different sizes
Dialogue: 0,0:32:52.05,0:32:55.15,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,不同的形状 那个区域石头里的所有碎片\N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}different shapes, all pieces of the rock that are in the area that
Dialogue: 0,0:32:55.18,0:32:57.28,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,都是碰撞压实的 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}impacting body impacted.
Dialogue: 0,0:32:58.56,0:33:01.54,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,在地球上就没有看到过这样的 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}We have just not seen anything like this on Earth.
Dialogue: 0,0:33:03.12,0:33:06.98,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,月球吃透不久就开始讲述了迷人的故事 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}The Moon rocks soon began to tell a fascinating tale.
Dialogue: 0,0:33:10.47,0:33:13.96,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,首先石头和土壤的样本包含的粒子\N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}First the rocks and soil samples contain particles
Dialogue: 0,0:33:14.24,0:33:18.36,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,标志了在形成之前月球必定覆盖了厚厚的\N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}indicating that the Moon must have been covered by a deep ocean of lava
Dialogue: 0,0:33:18.48,0:33:20.06,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,广阔的火山熔岩 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}after it formed.
Dialogue: 0,0:33:23.27,0:33:25.04,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,这个从发现得到的补充概念\N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}This notion was reinforced
Dialogue: 0,0:33:25.11,0:33:28.24,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,是石头缺少值得注意的\N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}by the discovery that the rocks were lacking significantly
Dialogue: 0,0:33:28.42,0:33:31.32,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,被科学家称之为"挥发性成分"的东西 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}in what scientists call "volatile elements".
Dialogue: 0,0:33:34.35,0:33:38.18,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,挥发性成分是那些容易挥发的元素 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}Volatile elements are those that can evaporate easily
Dialogue: 0,0:33:38.42,0:33:41.23,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,是在加热石头时会消失的 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}and they're for be lost when you heat up a rock.
Dialogue: 0,0:33:41.31,0:33:46.03,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,挥发性成分一些例子包括水或钾等等 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}And some examples of volatile elements include water or potassium for example.
Dialogue: 0,0:33:46.51,0:33:49.96,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,如果将地球岩石与月球岩石比较 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}And if you compare the bulk Earth rocks to lunar rocks
Dialogue: 0,0:33:50.05,0:33:52.89,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,会发现月球岩石非常的干 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}you find that lunar rocks are extremely parched.
Dialogue: 0,0:33:53.31,0:33:55.50,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,就象被加热过的 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}It's like just they've been heated and they've
Dialogue: 0,0:33:55.50,0:33:58.31,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,就象失去了挥发性成分 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}lost a lot of their volatile elements.
Dialogue: 0,0:33:59.67,0:34:02.16,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,但是顺着这个对比 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}But along with this start contrasts,
Dialogue: 0,0:34:02.19,0:34:06.62,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,月球样本也显示出在月球表面与\N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}the lunar samples also revealed at least one astonishing similarity
Dialogue: 0,0:34:06.68,0:34:10.39,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,地球上的岩石土壤之间至少有一个令人吃惊的相似之处 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}between the lunar surface and rocks and soil from Earth.
Dialogue: 0,0:34:11.31,0:34:16.36,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,个别元素的同位素象氧有些特别 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}The isotopes of individual elements, like oxygen in particular.
Dialogue: 0,0:34:17.24,0:34:18.81,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,氧有不同的形态 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}There are different forms of oxygen.
Dialogue: 0,0:34:19.38,0:34:23.54,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,月球与地球相比 有这不同形态的相同比率 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}The Moon had exactly the same ratios of different forms that the Earth did.
Dialogue: 0,0:34:24.43,0:34:27.31,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,但是我们掌握的来自太阳系其它地方的所有石块 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}But all the other rocks we knew from elsewhere in the solar system
Dialogue: 0,0:34:27.37,0:34:32.33,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,那些从太空落下的陨石 都具有不同的氧同位素的比率 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}which are meteorites that fall out of space, all have different oxygen isotope ratios.
Dialogue: 0,0:34:32.41,0:34:36.87,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,那些东西表明月球的物质与地球的物质非常非常地相似 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}Which tells you that the Moon material and the Earth material are very very similar.
Dialogue: 0,0:34:39.79,0:34:43.87,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,最后月球样本提供了关于月球地质构造的\N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}In the end the lunar samples had supplied a will for hard evidence,
Dialogue: 0,0:34:43.98,0:34:46.74,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,一个有力的证据 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}regarding the geological make up of the moon.
Dialogue: 0,0:34:49.08,0:34:52.04,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,然而天文学家试图了解月球的起源\N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}But astronomers trying to understand the Moon's origin
Dialogue: 0,0:34:52.09,0:34:54.28,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,仍然感到困惑..\N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}were still left with the puzzle.
Dialogue: 0,0:35:00.18,0:35:05.07,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,对于亚利桑那州图森的行星科学学会的威廉·哈特曼 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}For William Hartmann, of the Planetary Science Institute in Tucson, Arizona,
Dialogue: 0,0:35:05.20,0:35:08.71,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,月球石块透露的一点信息支持了一些想法 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}the information gleam from the Moon rocks supported some ideas
Dialogue: 0,0:35:08.75,0:35:11.66,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,他几乎研究了十年 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}he's been working on for nearly a decade.
Dialogue: 0,0:35:12.89,0:35:16.38,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,现在一位著名的天文学家兼太空画家 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}Now a distinguished astronomer and painter of space images,
Dialogue: 0,0:35:16.45,0:35:21.03,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,60年代早期哈特曼是亚利桑那大学的研究生 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}in the early 60s Hartmann was a graduate student at the University of Arizona,
Dialogue: 0,0:35:21.38,0:35:25.20,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,参与了一个项目 为月球冲击坑绘制地图 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}taking part in a project to map impact craters on the Moon.
Dialogue: 0,0:35:25.94,0:35:30.92,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,从巨大的盆地 或许多看得见的最小的坑着手 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}From the enormous basins, or seas to the smallest visible dimples.
Dialogue: 0,0:35:32.28,0:35:34.85,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,这一切我认识到 在60年代绘制的大盆地的地图\N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}All I realized during this mapping in the 60s
Dialogue: 0,0:35:34.91,0:35:38.24,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,实际上是撞击的特征 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}that the big basins are actually impact features.
Dialogue: 0,0:35:39.25,0:35:42.06,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,很大的小行星撞击了月球 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}Very large asteroids hit the Moon
Dialogue: 0,0:35:42.52,0:35:46.24,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,产生了这些巨大的爆发 某些宽达600英里 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}and made these huge explosions, some of them are 600 miles across.
Dialogue: 0,0:35:46.32,0:35:50.53,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,到底是多大的物体做到了这一点？大概有100英里宽 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}How big an object does it take to do that? Something like 100 miles across.
Dialogue: 0,0:35:50.95,0:35:54.78,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,所以有大的物体游荡在太阳系里 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}So we had large object surrounding around the inner solar system
Dialogue: 0,0:35:54.82,0:35:58.29,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,当地球形成时 撞击着行星 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}as the Earth was forming and they were crashing into planets.
Dialogue: 0,0:36:00.83,0:36:05.85,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,对于那个100英里宽的小行星撞击行星的概念 哈特曼\N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}For Hartman, the notion that a 100 miles wide asteroid once impacted planets
Dialogue: 0,0:36:06.23,0:36:08.35,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,提出了两个问题 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}bade a couple of questions.
Dialogue: 0,0:36:09.83,0:36:13.19,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,行星大小的物体曾经碰撞过吗？\N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}Could planet sized objects have ever collided?
Dialogue: 0,0:36:13.80,0:36:17.74,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,能够与月球的形成有关联吗？\N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}And could that have something to do with the formation of the Moon?
Dialogue: 0,0:36:19.84,0:36:24.85,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,1972年哈特曼和伙伴图森天文学家唐·戴维斯\N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}By 1972 Hartmann and fellow Tucson astronomer Don Davis
Dialogue: 0,0:36:25.35,0:36:29.35,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,编写了一个计算机程序帮助解决这些问题 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}had created a computer program to help them explore these ideas.
Dialogue: 0,0:36:33.25,0:36:35.49,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,程序粗略地模拟了\N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}The program made a rough attempt to simulate
Dialogue: 0,0:36:35.50,0:36:38.77,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,早期太阳系的成长过程 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}the accretion process in the early solar system.
Dialogue: 0,0:36:39.67,0:36:43.17,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,天文学家们希望看到会有其它行星物体\N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}The astronomers wanted to see if any others planetary bodies
Dialogue: 0,0:36:43.22,0:36:46.52,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,在地球附近形成 并能够撞击她 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}formed near the Earth and could have crashed into it.
Dialogue: 0,0:36:50.32,0:36:53.62,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,这个概念是…如果那里有一些其它的物体 \NThe idea was… if there was some other body there
Dialogue: 0,0:36:53.66,0:36:55.32,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,并且最终撞击地球 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}and it finally crashes into the Earth,
Dialogue: 0,0:36:55.34,0:36:58.16,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,将从地球撞出这所有的地壳物质…\Nit blows off all this crustal material from the Earth…
Dialogue: 0,0:36:58.89,0:37:01.39,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,同样也有撞击者自身 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}As well as from the impacter itself.
Dialogue: 0,0:37:03.19,0:37:05.09,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,可能月球是在那个外面形成的 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}Maybe the Moon could form out of that.
Dialogue: 0,0:37:05.49,0:37:08.99,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,确实充分的模拟表明第二个行星\N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}Sure enough the simulation showed that a second planet
Dialogue: 0,0:37:09.01,0:37:11.81,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,会在地球默认的地带形成 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}could have formed in the Earth's acquiescent zone.
Dialogue: 0,0:37:12.21,0:37:14.21,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,其大小相当于火星的大小 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}One about the size of Mars.
Dialogue: 0,0:37:15.11,0:37:19.51,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,那不是月球 因为它与地球有着相同的元素 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}It wasn't the Moon because it had formed from the same elements as the Earth
Dialogue: 0,0:37:19.54,0:37:23.84,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,所以它应该有着与地球一样的铁核和密度 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}and should therefore have had the same iron-core and heavy density as the Earth.
Dialogue: 0,0:37:25.34,0:37:27.34,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,月球当然不是这样的 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}The Moon of course does not.
Dialogue: 0,0:37:28.24,0:37:32.94,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,哈特曼足够的证据陈述了新的第四个假设 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}That was evidence enough for Hartmann to formulate a new fourth hypothesis.
Dialogue: 0,0:37:33.54,0:37:38.24,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,被称为 巨大撞击理论 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}It came to be called: The Giant Impact theory.
Dialogue: 0,0:37:46.44,0:37:51.83,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,1974年 解释地球的卫星来源的新假设 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}In 1974 a new hypothesis explaining the origin of Earth's moon
Dialogue: 0,0:37:51.85,0:37:55.03,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,登上了世界科学的舞台 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}debuted on the world scientific stage.
Dialogue: 0,0:37:55.23,0:37:59.03,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,它的支持者赋予它 巨大撞击理论 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}Its proponents dubbed it: The Giant Impact theory.
Dialogue: 0,0:38:01.73,0:38:05.03,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,基本的概念是大约在45亿年前 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}The basic idea is that about 4.5 billion years ago
Dialogue: 0,0:38:05.17,0:38:09.43,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,地球被相当于现在的火星大小的物体撞击 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}Earth collided with an object roughly the size of the current planet Mars.
Dialogue: 0,0:38:13.93,0:38:15.53,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,这是非常巨大的撞击 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}It's a very large collision.
Dialogue: 0,0:38:16.37,0:38:18.27,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,她使得地球自转 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}And it started the Earth's spinning.
Dialogue: 0,0:38:22.07,0:38:25.07,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,我们认为她带来了今天的一天24小时 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}It's what gave us our current 24 hour day we believe.
Dialogue: 0,0:38:27.17,0:38:28.77,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,这个撞击是如此的沉重 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}And this collision was so massive
Dialogue: 0,0:38:28.80,0:38:32.00,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,使得抛出的物质进入了围绕地球的轨道 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}that it launched material into orbit around the Earth.
Dialogue: 0,0:38:32.54,0:38:35.94,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,而且对于那些物质 我们认为随后凝聚成了月球 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}And it's for that material that we believe the Moon later coalesced.
Dialogue: 0,0:38:41.74,0:38:46.04,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,博尔的西南研究学会的罗宾·坎努普博士等人\N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}Dr. Robin Canup and others of the Southwest Research Institute in Boulder
Dialogue: 0,0:38:46.26,0:38:49.66,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,建立了一个计算机模型来研究\N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}have constructed a computer model to study the details
Dialogue: 0,0:38:49.76,0:38:52.16,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,巨大撞击设想的细节 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}of the giant impact scenario.
Dialogue: 0,0:38:54.66,0:38:58.36,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,她把地球和这个碰撞的粗野的原行星分别\N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}It divides off the Earth and this colliding rough protoplanet
Dialogue: 0,0:38:58.38,0:39:04.88,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,放入不同的粒子 接着不同粒子通过碰撞进行演变 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}into many different particles and then the evolution of each particle is tracked through the course of the impact.
Dialogue: 0,0:39:06.18,0:39:11.11,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,模拟通过从上往下鸟瞰描述碰撞 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}The simulation depicts the impact from a bird's eye view from the top-down.
Dialogue: 0,0:39:11.74,0:39:15.44,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,地球甚至在撞击之前可能部分熔化了 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}The Earth was probably partly molten even before this impact.
Dialogue: 0,0:39:19.14,0:39:22.04,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,所以最初碰撞在这个方向开始 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}So initially the impacter came in from this direction,
Dialogue: 0,0:39:22.54,0:39:25.54,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,她撞击地球是个偏心的撞击 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}it hit the Earth with an off-center collision.
Dialogue: 0,0:39:27.34,0:39:30.84,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,可以看到撞击延伸出来 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}And you can see the impacter has been stretched out
Dialogue: 0,0:39:30.86,0:39:34.66,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,形成物质的长臂 就在这 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}into this long arm of material, right here.
Dialogue: 0,0:39:36.16,0:39:38.86,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,科学家认为地球的上层\N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}Scientists believe the upper layers of the Earth
Dialogue: 0,0:39:38.89,0:39:42.16,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,随着撞击完全熔化 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}became completely molten following the impact.
Dialogue: 0,0:39:43.06,0:39:44.86,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,撞击让地球开始旋转 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}The collision starts the Earth rotating.
Dialogue: 0,0:39:46.96,0:39:49.74,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,同样能够看到撞击\N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}And you can also see that the collision has
Dialogue: 0,0:39:49.95,0:39:52.97,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,充分扭曲了地球本身的形状 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}substantially distorted the shape of the Earth itself.
Dialogue: 0,0:39:55.47,0:39:59.77,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,几个小时后 看到撞击物质形成的长臂\N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}After a couple hours we see that this arm of impacter material
Dialogue: 0,0:40:00.17,0:40:03.67,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,由于引力崩塌成两个大块 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}has collapsed gravitationally into two large clumps.
Dialogue: 0,0:40:04.17,0:40:07.47,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,里面的大块\N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}The inner clump of the impacter material
Dialogue: 0,0:40:07.97,0:40:11.53,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,实际上无可厚非 是撞击者的核 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}is actually composed overwhelmingly of the impacter's core.
Dialogue: 0,0:40:12.03,0:40:15.53,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,所以当这个里面的大块与地球碰撞时 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}So then when this inner clump recollides with the Earth,
Dialogue: 0,0:40:16.33,0:40:18.33,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,她发生在这里 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}and it happens right there,
Dialogue: 0,0:40:21.53,0:40:25.23,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,大多数的铁随着碰撞\N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}the vast majority of the iron that came in with the impacter
Dialogue: 0,0:40:25.63,0:40:27.73,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,实际上由地球收集起来了 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}is actually accumulated by the Earth.
Dialogue: 0,0:40:30.79,0:40:32.28,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,而外面的大块 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}While this outer clump
Dialogue: 0,0:40:32.51,0:40:35.25,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,靠近地球运行 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}comes and it makes a close pass by the Earth,
Dialogue: 0,0:40:36.23,0:40:40.32,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,在地球的引力作用下 撕开变为一条物质的长臂 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}and is stripped by the Earth's gravity into a long arm of material,
Dialogue: 0,0:40:40.35,0:40:42.81,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,接着破裂成为这个圆盘 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}which then breaks up to form this disk.
Dialogue: 0,0:40:44.81,0:40:49.81,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,上面提到的物质紧接着沉重的撞击 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}The material is taught to have coalesced to form the Moon in less than an year,
Dialogue: 0,0:40:50.31,0:40:52.31,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,在不到一年的时间里结合形成了月球 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}following the massive impact.
Dialogue: 0,0:40:58.11,0:41:00.91,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,现在的地球上已经没有那次碰撞的痕迹 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}There is no sign of this impact on the Earth today
Dialogue: 0,0:41:01.21,0:41:06.61,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,这是因为当时 地球的大小只有现在大小的90%左右 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}because at the time, our planet it only developed to about 90% of its current size.
Dialogue: 0,0:41:07.11,0:41:11.51,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,余下的10%是在以后的许多小得多的碰撞中形成的 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}The remaining 10% would accumulate from later much smaller impacts.
Dialogue: 0,0:41:13.21,0:41:16.81,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,地球本身的引力也重新进行了改造 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}Also the Earth's own gravity had a reshaping effect.
Dialogue: 0,0:41:18.11,0:41:21.71,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,在发生碰撞以后的日子里 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}Within the day after the impact the Earth had reassumed
Dialogue: 0,0:41:22.15,0:41:24.21,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,地球再次形成了基本的球状 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}a basically spherical shape.
Dialogue: 0,0:41:24.71,0:41:29.75,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,碰撞引起的所有凹地被抹平了 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}And any depression that the impact caused would had been smoothed over.
Dialogue: 0,0:41:31.05,0:41:34.05,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,巨大碰撞理论的发明人比尔·哈特曼\N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}Giant Impact theory originator Bill Hartmann
Dialogue: 0,0:41:34.15,0:41:38.95,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,在1974年的科学讨论会上介绍了他的假设 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}presented his hypothesis at a scientific conference in 1974.
Dialogue: 0,0:41:42.15,0:41:45.85,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,然而在近十年里 很少得到关注 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}But it received little attention for nearly a decade.
Dialogue: 0,0:41:47.05,0:41:51.05,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,对月球的兴趣在阿波罗任务的最后急剧地降温 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}Interest in the Moon dropped off sharply at the end of the Apollo missions.
Dialogue: 0,0:41:57.75,0:42:01.75,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,最后在1984年夏威夷的月球研讨会上 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}Finally at a lunar conference in Hawaii in 1984
Dialogue: 0,0:42:02.05,0:42:04.25,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,距离最后一次月球发射12年以后 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}twelve years after the last Moon shot,
Dialogue: 0,0:42:04.35,0:42:08.35,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,世界上最大的四个天文学组织达成一个共识 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}the world's four most astronomers reached a consensus.
Dialogue: 0,0:42:10.03,0:42:14.13,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,巨大碰撞理论是确定月球来源\N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}The Giant Impact theory was the most acceptable explanation to date
Dialogue: 0,0:42:14.17,0:42:16.17,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,最可接受的解释 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}for the origin of the Moon.
Dialogue: 0,0:42:17.31,0:42:21.71,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,我想还是有人会说 "好啦 至今还是没有被证明啊 "\N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}I think there's still some people who say: "Ok, it's not really proving yet."
Dialogue: 0,0:42:22.14,0:42:24.51,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,但是这就是我称之为有待证明的理论 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}But it's what I would call the default theory.
Dialogue: 0,0:42:24.74,0:42:28.31,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,如果你翻阅所有行星科学或地质学的教科书 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}If you look at any textbook of planetary science or geology
Dialogue: 0,0:42:28.54,0:42:30.14,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,这就是公认的理论 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}it's just the theory that's accepted.
Dialogue: 0,0:42:30.54,0:42:33.84,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,在已经解释的地方必然会有些小的矛盾 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}And there are certain small discrepancies which have yet to be explained
Dialogue: 0,0:42:33.94,0:42:35.64,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,但是大部分是认可的 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}but buy in large it works.
Dialogue: 0,0:42:42.44,0:42:46.14,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,即使有一个关于月球来源的意见一致的理论 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}Even with an agreed-upon theory of how our moon came to be
Dialogue: 0,0:42:46.64,0:42:52.85,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,科学家还是没有结束用各种手段对我们最近的邻居的研究 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}scientists have not finished studying our closest cosmic neighbor by any means.
Dialogue: 0,0:42:54.45,0:42:58.95,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,事实上讨论重返月球表面建立永久前哨基地 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}In fact talk of returning to the lunar surface with a permanent end outpost
Dialogue: 0,0:42:59.37,0:43:03.25,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,最近从白宫到航天局开始了 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}has recently emanated from the Whitehouse at NASA headquarters.
Dialogue: 0,0:43:07.45,0:43:09.25,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,窗前灿烂的光芒 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}Gorgeous heat is at the window.
Dialogue: 0,0:43:10.31,0:43:12.15,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,一路顺风 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}Exec-One's good everything go.
Dialogue: 0,0:43:14.15,0:43:19.65,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,这样的基地能够提供训练宇航员长期在太空生活的地方 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}Such a base could provide a place to train astronauts to live in space long term.
Dialogue: 0,0:43:20.04,0:43:24.74,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,以及提供更有效的发射点 最终实现火星飞行 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}As well as provide them more efficient launch point for eventual missions to Mars.
Dialogue: 0,0:43:28.65,0:43:33.75,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,但是这崇高的科学目标是来自远方的地球的精神 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}But such lofty scientific goals are far from the minds of average residence of Earth.
Dialogue: 0,0:43:34.25,0:43:39.45,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,人们偶尔凝视夜晚天空生动催眠的圆月 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}Who occasionally peer up at the glowing mesmerizing lunar disk in the night sky.
Dialogue: 0,0:43:42.95,0:43:45.45,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,对于我们讨论熔岩海洋…\NFor us talk of lava oceans…
Dialogue: 0,0:43:47.25,0:43:49.45,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,风化层形成了微小陨石…\NRegolith forming micrometeorites…
Dialogue: 0,0:43:50.74,0:43:52.44,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,以及巨大的碰撞…\NAnd giant impacts…
Dialogue: 0,0:43:53.64,0:43:59.44,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,将永远不会削弱我们对那个神秘邻居的魅力与追求 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}Will never diminish the fascination and romance of our mysterious neighbor-world:
Dialogue: 0,0:44:00.67,0:44:02.37,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,月球 \N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}the Moon.
Dialogue: 0,0:44:03.00,0:44:08.00,*Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,谢谢观赏\N{\fnCronos Pro Subhead\fs14\1c&H3CF1F3&}Thanks For Viewing
